metadata.name: Insula #158
metadata.description:
An audiovisual collection.
.
Click to start the sound.
..
Insula is an endless generative music player.
...
There are 6 different grid size; 4 squares and 20 squares are the rare ones.

2 different background texture; Lines, Grain.

2 different color placement; Circular, Linear.

7 different noise types.

8 different scales with fixed root notes; C Maj., C Lydian, D Dorian, D Min. Penta., G Maj., G Maj. Penta., F Mixolydian, F Min.

2 different rhythmical structures; 2:3, 4:5.

2 different note indicator style; Circle and Square. Square is rare and behaves differently.

5 different note indicator line divisions.
....
Harmonization process based on Avro Part's 'Tintinnabuli' style.

Grid design inspired from Novation's Launchpad.


Made with p5.js and Web Audio.

Ilgın İçözü, December 2021
@distcollective

metadata.name: MOUNTAINS #48
metadata.description:
"MOUNTAINS" is a work that belongs to the "FLUX Series", which utilizes the same techniques and processes as the previous work "FLUX". The shape in this piece is created by placing elements using noise and then performing recursive pixel operations on these elements.

The inspiration behind this work came from my continued sketches and studies of Flow Field, which led me to discover an expression of objects that seemed to be corroding. I believed that by applying this technique, I could create a realistic and vivid sculpture from a geometric shape.In this work, this corrosion treatment is applied to a geometric triangular shape of overlapping rectangles to form a realistic and dynamic mountain landscape.
It was as if geometric figures like Plato's "ideas" were materialized in the real world.

Additionally,  I was also inspired by the mountain views from my hometown at New Year's and by the manga background paintings of Yoshiharu Tsuge, who specializes in depicting villages with old hot springs.

It is possible to get a 5760 x 3240 px png file by right click save.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any inquiries.

Artwork by hasaqui, @hasaqui.
Made with p5js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Chaotic Grid Symphony #56
metadata.description:
This code is a mesmerizing visual feast for the eyes, creating an animation of a dynamic grid of black and white squares that appear to be constantly shuffling in a seemingly random pattern.
The grid is made up of an mesmerizing 128 by 128 squares, each one seamlessly transitioning to its new state as the animation progresses.

At the heart of the animation is the use of the noise function, which adds a touch of randomness to the movement of the squares.
This, coupled with the use of the "frameCount" variable, ensures that the animation is always evolving and never repeats itself.
The switch statement is used to cleverly determine the movement of each square, making the grid appear to be a living, breathing organism.

The icing on the cake is the interactive element of the animation, where the user can reset the grid at any time by simply clicking on the canvas.
And, to top it all off, the canvas is perfectly sized to fit the window, making it an immersive experience.

metadata.name: Canevach #263
metadata.description:
Canevach started as a code golfing experiment, 280 characters of HTML, CSS and JavaScript producing pixelated patterns when copy-pasted in the address bar of a web browser.

The code has been adapted for the sake of entropy control and readability, but I tried to keep it as lean as possible to honour the code golfing spirit that initiated the project.

The artwork is generated by manipulating pixels directly through the Canvas API.

Colours are uniformly selected in RGB space, without any colour theory considerations. The only exception is for black, which is made more prominent by the way the algorithm is initiated.

Features
• Canvas size: 8x8 | 16x16 | 32x32 | 64x64 | 128x128
• Number of colours: 1 to 5

fx(hash) Generative Token by loackme

metadata.name: Audio Spelunk #14
metadata.description:
Interactive generative sound. Tap to start. Tap repeatedly to explore the sound space.

Here I continue my work in low-level audio glitch by direct manipulation of the digital audio buffer. Distorted loops are generated in real-time and played losslessly in your browser through Web Audio. Audioreactive visualizations are powered by p5js.

Rarity features: the least common traits are stereo, thick, lines, grayscale, pink, cyan, white, and inverted.

Controls:
- Start sound: tap/click anywhere.
- Next sound: tap/click anywhere or press any key.
- Depth counter: tap/click lower-left corner or press 'd'.
- Mute: tap/click lower-right corner or press 'm'.

metadata.name: Curtains #112
metadata.description:
Curtains

While learning more about flow fields, as an intermediate step, the first version of this came out.
The artwork creates a set of lines; the first point of the lines are anchors, which can be in a straight line, sinus wave, or tangent function.
The second point is set by calculating the angle from the first using Perlin noise.

The project features 10 different hand-picked color schemes.

Actions:
--------------
Press [s] to save
--------------


Created using p5.js

metadata.name: deserts and mountains #97
metadata.description:
Two different types of landscapes that have some distinct characteristics.


Deserts are dry, arid regions that receive very little rainfall. They are often characterized by hot temperatures, sparse vegetation, and sandy or rocky terrain. There are several different types of deserts, including hot and dry, coastal, and semi-arid deserts.

Mountains are areas of elevated land that rise significantly above the surrounding terrain. They are formed through a variety of geological processes, and can range in size and shape.


One key difference between deserts and mountains is their climate.
Deserts have very dry and hot climates, while mountains can have a wide range of climates, depending on their location and elevation.

metadata.name: Zazzle #4
metadata.description:
A contemporary tribute to the retro look of the '70s. It incorporates pulsating shapes and colors that evoke the nostalgia of these time periods, but revisits them in an abstract, modern way. 

Using a combination of algorithmic processes, this work produces visually distinctive patterns and textures. 

The created perceptual patterns come together to energetically form a piece that captures the essence of these classical times.


- On Live mode press ’D’ to save in JPG

- Made by p5js'

metadata.name: Element #141
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Mythologic #123
metadata.description:
"Mythologic" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

Mythologic is a project derived from cloud series, Cloud Atlas and Requiem: Cloud on fxhash. In the series, lines and circles are used in an organics movement like Cloud Hands, which is a move of Tai Chi. Practitioners move their hands slowly and smoothly, make circles and rotate with extreme concentrating. In Chinese we said “floating clouds and flowing water” to describe calligraphers’ freely flowing style of writing. Chi is a very important for oriental artists, and for genart as well. In the series, lines and circles start from one position to another, and develop with organic rotations and movements, like practicing Tai Chi on the canvas. 

Mythologic was inspired from “Classic of Mountains and Seas”, also known as Shan Hai Jing, is a Chinese classic text and a compilation of mythic geography and beasts. 

“There is a beast that looks like a fox with nine tails.” 
“Huangbei: it is a beetle with meat like a tadpole, but with a head and a tail” 
“The beast has the body of a fish but the wings of a bird” 

There are many incredible creatures in the text which describe the oriental fantasy. The idea of Mythologic is to present an illustrated handbook with random generated paintings, each one is like a framed badge, to memorize the glorious age. It uses the "cloud hands" technique in every parts of this piece, the center, the circle and the frame. They are all the same algorithm but perform variety with different density and components. Gold, Silver, Copper, Jade and Ruby colors as noble symbol of treasure in Chinese culture. 

This project use p5js. 

Press 'S' to save pictures.

Thanks to the support of Yi-Wen Lin in this project.

metadata.name: Doors of Perception #43
metadata.description:
The title of this work is inspired by Aldous Huxley's book of the same name, exploring ideas of conciousness.

Inspiration is found in the places we choose to look. I have been personally motivated to learn p5js from scratch, to be able to mint this, my very first generative artwork. This motivation came from seeing the work of others right here on fxhash.

Aldous Huxley himself took the title for his book from the William Blake poem 'The Marriage of Heaven and Hell';

“If the doors of perception were cleansed every thing would appear to man as it is: Infinite. For man has closed himself up, till he sees all things thro' narrow chinks of his cavern”

I hope my work inspires you in some small way.

Whilst each mint will be infinitely unique, there are no intentional rarity traits. Variations are made in door count, frame split, colours, and speed.

Press 's' to save .png

metadata.name: Grove #142
metadata.description:
A generative, impressionist painting of a small grove of trees in one of the four seasons. In spring and summer, flowers bloom in the meadow. A rare variation will create a charcoal drawing on white or black paper. Super rare will create a lighted winter scene that may have a moon behind the tree.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press 's' to save a screenshot at any point. Image size is 1400x1082px.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 3,000 px.

On the paintings only, adding '&bg=true' will stop the painting after the background. Adding '&size=3000&bg=true' will give you a nice desktop background! 

Common Features:
- About 12-14 trees
- One of the four seasons
- One of 12 highlight color tints
- One of 12 shadow color tints
- Varying levels of distance haze
- Varying max brush sizes
- Varying amount of colors in the strokes

Less Common
- 15% chance of a charcoal drawing
- 50% chance it to be a dark winter scene

Rare
- Winter drawing with lights on the tree

Super Rare
- Winter drawing with a moon behind the tree

metadata.name: Digital Surface 3 #39
metadata.description:
The mechanics of Digital Surface are inspired by nature and the aesthetics by pixels. Digital Surface is an attempt to find an autonomous visual logic for a digital world made by machines.
The image is created one pixel after another, calculating the proceeding pixel based on the previous generations.
The color palettes are influenced by colors occurring in nature mixed with artificial man made colors that we see more today, aiming to look for new combinations that are pleasant to humans and natively digital.

 Once the image is completely rendered, press "s" to save in a small size, "m" in a medium, "l" in a large, "x" in a xlarge and "w" to save with the size of the window.

Digital Surface is a 5 series project. Each Series is released singularly, the third being Digital Surface 3. The main differentiation for series 3 is that each image can contains 4, 5 or 6 colors. This series contains the biggest part of the body of work.
This is Francesco Forcellini Studio's first NFT project broadening their field of work from physical to digital.

Built using p5js, published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.

Once the collection will be fully minted, the variations button will be disabled.
